            <TokenIdentifier>//apple_ref/occ/instm/UMController/awakeFromNib</TokenIdentifier>
            <Anchor>awakeFromNib</Anchor>
            <DeclaredIn>UMController.h</DeclaredIn>
            <Declaration>- (void)awakeFromNib</Declaration>
            <Abstract>Configures this status item and its menu. Then makes a call to captureStringsFromWebpage with a nil timer which kicks off the first query to the router (and in turn calls setStatusStrings). An NSTimer is then created and added to the current run loop. The timer's selector is captureStringsFromWebpage and it is hard-coded to fire every 3 minutes. </Abstract>
        </Token>
        <Token>
            <TokenIdentifier>//apple_ref/occ/instm/UMController/captureStringsFromWebpage:</TokenIdentifier>
            <Anchor>captureStringsFromWebpage:</Anchor>
            <DeclaredIn>UMController.h</DeclaredIn>
            <Declaration>- (void)captureStringsFromWebpage:(NSTimer *)timer </Declaration>
            <Abstract>Captures percentString, resetTime, violatedFapString, allowance, and allowanceRemaining from the contents of the router status page. The timer is ignored, but included so NSTimer can use this method as a selector.Notes: An NSURLRequest is created from the URL and the contents of the web page is converted to a string that is then searched to find the above mentioned instance variables. The request is made from inside a try/catch/finally block. If the request fails (probably because we are not connected to the atlas network and therefore there is no router to query) an exeception is thrown and the instance variables (precentString, resetTime, violatedFapString, allowance, and allowanceRemaining) are set to default values. Finally, setStatusStrings is called and the StatusItem title and the StatusItem menu items are set.</Abstract>
        </Token>
